text:
#barbietoo  before i left the house i made sure to dress in something loose that would not be too distracting. as i walk the streets of new york at night,one hand holds my groceries tightly, the other holds my pocket knife. i walk with urgency, my hoodie is up and my headphones in and,which are not playing music, act like a barrier between the men who catcalls and whistles at me. i see a masculine shadow at the end of the street, but i cannot see its owner. i fear it‚Äôs a man awaiting my passing. i make a detour and walk across the street. 
as i usually do on a weekend night, i was clubbing and hanging out with my girls. i normally go to gay clubs, but this weekend i went to a straight club.  once i felt a strong grip on my ass, i turned around to say what the hell, but this 6 foot tall frat guy in a polo would not look at me. this is the first time i  had my ass grabbed unsolicitedly. they have the balls to grab me, but they don‚Äôt own up to their actions. every 5 minutes i would take a headcount of my girls because the cocky boys would not listen to us when we said we did not want to grind with them. this was the first night where i saw that the boys were not listening to no. it made me wonder why they felt because it was dark and the music was loud that they could do what they want. i was not being listened to. ‚Äúthere is no greater threat to women than men? we‚Äôre the number one threat!‚Äù said louis c.k. in his hbo special. when are men taught to acknowledge boundaries? i should be able to leave and feel safe wherever i go without having to worry. i am tired with the way that men are treating me and other women. every women has there own story with harassment, but to tell mine i am using barbie as my proxy. when i was younger i looked up to her and she was a beacon of indepence and i vividly remember watching rapunzel barbie in my bubblegum pink room thinking ‚Äúlook at all that she can do for herself‚Äù. #photo #photography #art #camera #canon #fujifilm #fujitx1 #digital #digitalphoto #digitalphotography #digitalphotos #mirrorless #metoo #barbie #pink #hair #violent #ken #sexualassult

text:
these ladies, tameka palmer and rhonda a. thompson, are killing and stomping it!  my fellow advocates and honorees at the unsung heroes luncheon.  kimya motley gave me the warmest hug on this day!  thinking about it gives me chills. god made it so that the four of us are still here to share our survival stories. 
four authors! 
four survivors! 
four warriors! 
four empowerment speakers encouraging the masses!
#eachonereachone #nomore #nfl #domesticviolence #unsungheroes

every year during superbowl week, the nfl honors the advocates that fight domestic violence and sexual assault. i attended the unsung hero luncheon along with my fellow advocates. i am honored and humbled by this experience. 
i'm a shifted masterpiece.

text:
‚Ä¢anon seeks for your prayers and advice, be kind to drop one üíï‚Ä¢
one of the worst moments ever was when i took my mother to therapy. after a series of questions and a light chat, he asked her if she ever had suicidal urgencies, if she wanted to kill herself. my mother was hesitant to answer because i was there but she knew i'd understand i guess because she nodded a yes. that's it, that was when i felt my life had no meaning. i do my best to keep her happy and help her out, but its never enough. she says the same and at times taunts me about me. it's her son, the apple of her eyes. he can just walk into the room and my mother would have stars in her eyes. he doesn't even do anything and he gets the appreciation i deserve. i've grown to not let it affect me. her happiness is all that matters to me, even if it doesn't come from me. i've done and tried everything to help her prevent her suicidal tendencies but i can't. please help me out. every advice and prayer will mean a lot to me.
‚Ä¢

text:
i.  did i ever speak about how
many times i stayed quiet?

or about the time when 
the only thing i regretted 
was my resulting silence in situations that demanded rage?

sometimes what feels like defeat,
might just be survival. 
but-
sometimes, 
speaking is empowerment
speaking is liberation
speaking is growth.

ii.  when i speak, 
i speak for women
i speak for men
i also speak for me.

i speak for any and everyone,
who even once in their life 
told themselves
silence is survival and
broke themselves.

i speak for them,
anyone who feels 
more like a victim than they are, a survivor.

iii.  did i ever tell you that the men
on the bike
down a shady street
weren't just passerby's?
or 
did i ever tell you 
it wasn't a wallet 
brushing against me in the crowd?

iv.  did i ever tell you about the time 
when his toxic masculinity empowered him 
while my naivety overshadowed my consciousness? 
v.  did i ever tell you
about the strong and bold women
who broke down in front of me
because vulnerability wasnt an option they had
and they just needed a shoulder?

i didn't?
well now i did.
.
. -nush.v

text:
rise up!!!
be a part of the solution. so often we see things happening in our community and we take on the "that's none of my business mentality" or the "someone else will make the call mindset". but, saving our children from the grips of these predators has to be everyone's business!! sex abuse and sex trafficking are crimes of opportunity and access. but to a certain extent, these crimes can also thrive because of the apathy of those around the situation. if we all are watching out for and reporting suspicious activity and behavior, we can help put an end to it. if you see something, you must say something. the community (i.e. the village) has to take back the responsibility of looking out for the most vulnerable amongst us. if you are a victim or suspect that a child may be a victim of human trafficking, please call 911 or call the national human trafficking resource center at 1-888-373-7888 for help. all victims of slavery and human trafficking have rights and are protected by international, federal, and state law. 
the hotline is:‚Ä®(1) anonymous and confidential;‚Ä®(2) available 24 hours a day, seven days a week;‚Ä®(3) able to provide help, referral to services, training, and general information; (4) accessible in 170 languages;‚Ä®(5) operated by a nonprofit, nongovernmental organization; and‚Ä®(6) toll free. üì∏: @consultingexp #childsexabuseawareness #stopchildsexabuse #childsexabusesurvivor #parentsofchilldsexabusesurvivor #sexualassault #endchildsexabuse #endrapeculture #childabuse #sextrafficking #atlanta #atl #georgia #women #girls #teens #awareness #rapevictim #victim #children #prevention #trafficking  #survivor #tips #blogger #speaker #metoo #advocate #volunteer #activist  #superbowl

‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
üíç janet akie masamitsu / @janetjewelrynyc
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
‚ù£Ô∏èdoes your asian american identity inform your work/business? if so, how?
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
‚Äúi identify most with my father, a 2nd generation japanese american, who spent his teen years at camp manzanar. my dad went from living in a concentration camp, to being ranked the in the top 25 asian american entrepreneurs in america.  his work philosophy and work ethics, his optimism even during times of extreme hardships, his desire to give back to the community (his foundation‚Äôs main focus is to provide scholarships to underprivileged students)‚Äîit is rooted in his japanese american experience/identity, and that foundation is what drives me and my business.‚Äù
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
‚ù£Ô∏èhow do you stay motivated and/or creative while running a business?
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
‚Äúi make time every morning to do a quick am reflection for the day.  it helps me prioritize my day, while also entertaining my adhd brain, which is where most of my creativity dwells.  reflections help me connect the dots so that i can maintain focus on the big picture.‚Äù
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
‚ù£Ô∏ètell us about your dream project/collaborator.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
‚Äúmy dream project thus far, has been the one design i made for womankind, a non-profit org that helps survivors of gender based violence heal from their trauma.  i love that clients have told me it has been a conversation starter for them to talk to others about #metoo and #timesup. for a jewelry designer to have that kind of impact on a social justice issues that is close to my heart‚Äîthat has been a dream come true for me, and i hope to be able to continue this passion project for as long as i can.‚Äù

text:
what an inspiring way to end a week! congratulations to all the film-makers and organizers of this great event.
these thought-provoking films were followed by a great panel discussion (including two badass ladies, dr. aruna uprety and ramyata limbu) ranging from toxic masculinity, #metoo in the nepali context, and dealing with gender discrimination from a young age.
my favourite film was ‚Äò6,743 count my voice!‚Äô which explores challenges a dalit woman elected to be ward member faces in actually having meaningful participation.
if anyone is planning relevant events they can get access to the films for screening. they are a powerful way to start conversations about improving implementation of laws that as of now only exist on paper. would be great for government people to see them. #accountabilitylab

text:
let‚Äôs talk about the pineal gland and it‚Äôs connection to the third eye. the pineal gland is located in the center of the brain. you may have heard before that in activating the pineal gland you also create a vibration in the third eye, drawing energy to the space between your eye brows. so many of us struggle to active the pineal gland and get the vibration in the forehead. why? your pineal gland is calcified. think of calcification as a layer of smog over the gland. florescent light, computer screens (blue light) and fluoride are just a few examples of things that cause this calcification. how do you de-calcify? daily meditation practice, purple foods (as they are associated to the crown chakra - wild blueberries) sleep with selenite next to your pillow, salt lamps, switch your toothpaste to fluoride free and please spend less time in front of screens with blue light! i promise you - if you at the very least practice meditation everyday for two weeks straight - you will start to open up that channel and feel a physical vibration. that feeling leads to a state of euphoria and mental clarity/calm. enjoy the practice. because that‚Äôs all we can do... is practice.

text:
at this year‚Äôs sundance film festival, tarana burke, the activist and¬†founder of the #metoo movement, released a series of psas focused on sexual assault. in the animated videos, we hear the voices of survivors as they chronicle their own experiences with sexual violence. among them include actor terry crews, who in response¬†to the allegations of sexual assault leveled against harvey weinstein,¬†revealed¬†in october 2017 that he was the survivor of a sexual assault by a ‚Äúhigh-level hollywood executive‚Äù (later discovered to be¬†adam venit, now formerly of william morris endeavor). Ôøº

burke spoke on the importance of incorporating male voices into the #metoo movement as it moves forward. ‚Äúas a first media project that we're coming out with, it was definitely important to include male voices, because we're really trying to underscore and emphasize that this is not a woman's movement,‚Äù she¬†explained in an interview with refinery29. ‚Äúthere's just not enough conversation about male survivors, about men and boys who survived child sexual abuse, or men who experienced sexual harassment.‚Äù touching on crews specifically, burke went on to note, ‚Äúas we've seen with terry crews, it's very evidenced by his case, that men who come forward are ridiculed, and shunned, and treated unfairly.‚Äù it is not easy for any survivor of sexual assault to come forward, but there are specific challenges that a male survivor may face. most of those challenges are a direct result of the attitudes of other men, the pressure that urges men to be unassailable.

that has been the case for crews since he shared his testimony of being sexually assaulted on twitter. in having a¬†large platform and speaking openly about his experiences, crews has done everything in his power to prevent his story from being silenced or misconstrued, but all too often, voices like his are suppressed.

bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

cnn

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text:
1 in 4 women and 1 in 9 men experience severe intimate partner physical violence, intimate partner contact sexual violence, and/or intimate partner stalking with impacts such as injury, fearfulness, ptsd, etc
.
in the u.s., 1  in 3 women and 1 in 6 men experienced some form of contact sexual violence in their lifetime
.
what we can do?
.
1. believe survivors. if someone close to you confides their story to you about abuse, assault or violence it‚Äôs is overwhelmingly likely they are telling the truth. the first step to empower victims is to tell them you believe them. the days of victim blaming, shaming and non-believing are over.
.
2. educate. as a sexual assault survivor, i am now dedicating myself to education on domestic and sexual violence and advocacy. i‚Äôm asking questions. trying to learn. and i‚Äôm talking about it. it‚Äôs not a cozy conversation but it‚Äôs real and happening right in front of your eyes with the people you‚Äôre closest too. learn. educate yourself on the statistics. advocate for the survivors you know. take a stand. be brave and have the hard conversations.
.
3. step up and step in. it‚Äôs not always easy to step in, even if you know it‚Äôs the right thing to do. some common reasons bystanders and witnesses remain on the sidelines include:
‚Äúi don‚Äôt know what to do or what to say.‚Äù
‚Äúi don‚Äôt want to cause a scene.‚Äù
‚Äúit‚Äôs not my business.‚Äù
‚Äúi don‚Äôt want my friend to be mad at me.‚Äù
‚Äúi‚Äôm sure someone else will step in.‚Äù
it‚Äôs okay to have these thoughts, but it‚Äôs important to realize that your actions can have a big impact. in many situations, bystanders have the opportunity to prevent crimes like sexual assault from happening in the first place. and when you have witnessed speak up, you can help prevent the abuser from attacking again. .
our voices do matter. speak the truth even when it‚Äôs hard. even if friends turn their back. even if witnesses change their story for personal gain or because they are too fearful. even if powerful people and corporations try to silence you. even if you are scared. even though beginning to tell my own story from 20 months ago is hard, i know i‚Äôm walking in absolute truth and integrity. #believesurvivors #metoo üôè

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text:
#metoo tide has swayed the social media right since october'17. although, the phrase first came in use in the year 2006, the hashtag on twitter made it turn into a movement that reached the doors of the us congress. over 80 women alleged harvey weinstein of sexual abuse, the first person to fall prey to this movement. the famous 'weinstein effect' is named after him, which is grabbing hold of all those men who are misusing their power. 
no wonder, this movement has given many women the courage to be strong and stand up against the harassment they have faced or any other odds they have faced. many women who couldn't open up to the police used the social media to share their story. but few have misused the social media platform and accused men of hoax allegations. they have targeted the paparazzi to be paparazzi themselves. ¬†these allegations don't have any standby or any solid proof. unfortunately, media gossip is transformed to judgments and people try to take the supremacy of courts in their hands.

voices of the 8-year old asifa bano and others are still demanding justice. but the media is more carried away by the glamour of the film industry.people might have forgotten 'kathua' but time has captured every glimpse of that dreadful moment in its lap.

decades of waiting to get justice has shook the very essence of faith that people have in the law and the constitution. few have turned to be rebellious due to this and want seek justice on their own.

its time we all realize this and take charge of our own karmas. as karma doesn't hold back for any one. 
#metoo #f4f #l4l  #india #geu

text:
the shadow is the unconscious part of our psyche. neither good nor bad, it contains the elements that we are called to consciously call forth and integrate over a lifetime on the journey to our whole selves.
-
over the years i‚Äôve noticed that we often express ourselves as the exact opposite of what our shadows are, crafting an identity and public life that serves the compensatory function of telling people exactly who we aren‚Äôt.
-
we construct our external reality to make up for the stuff we‚Äôre not addressing internally.
-
working out our shadows is very difficult, it‚Äôs easier to put on grand ceremonies that signal to others what we‚Äôd like to be, if only we weren‚Äôt who we actually are. companies are built, nations are conquered, because of this.
-
i call this ‚Äúleading with the opposite.‚Äù social media helps us along with it in our personal lives, but the most outrageous examples are found where power is centralized:
-
the ‚Äúsocial impact‚Äù organizations led by tyrants who mistreat their employees and partners.
-
the spiritual teachers who speak of awareness and self-control while taking advantage of their students and living out narcissistic guru complexes.
-
the seasoned meditators who maintain a heavy cycle of retreats in their calendar and are conflict avoidant, using spiritual ‚Äúcredentials‚Äù to rise above actually addressing real relationship issues.
-
the politicians who...
-
and so on.
-
looking behind trump‚Äôs wall obsession reveals his own lack of boundaries and internal structure - a personal shadow seeking an external compensation.
-
because the shadow is the unconscious, unintegrated side of our psyche, it will ultimately express itself through our actions and words when we‚Äôre not carefully editing them. shakespeare articulated this swiftly with ‚Äúthou dost protest too much.‚Äù
-
time will always reveal what our shadows are, no matter how many layers of messaging we add to suggest their opposite.
-
the invitation is always for us: what are we ‚Äúleading with‚Äù that is compensating for something not yet worked out in ourselves?

text:
windy cloudy day today, after the cleansing rains.... makes me think of how i receive and flow with the currents and energies of life. do i bend with the gales of wind, going where the higher mind of me life wants to take me? or do i get all rigid and resistant with my sorry excuses and fears, refusing to step out of my known and comfortable box?

do i give myself the gift of being washed cleaned by the waters of life? or do i encourage the growth of dead rotting things in my life and body because i refuse to let go? 
how well do i bathe my body by drinking in the life giving, cleansing waters of pure juices and fluids that flush away the inner toxic debris? 
can i allow the waters of my tears to fall, cleansing my being of old unexpressed emotions and unresolved experiences that would harden me, closing me off to the life giving light of the sun and wandering winds of life?

are you receiving and flowing with the currents, the waters and energies of your life? or is there something or someone you are resisting, arguing and fighting against?
name: Loralee Humpherys

windy cloudy day today, after the cleansing rains.... makes me think of how i receive and flow with the currents and energies of life. do i bend with the gales of wind, going where the higher mind of me life wants to take me? or do i get all rigid and resistant with my sorry excuses and fears, refusing to step out of my known and comfortable box?

do i give myself the gift of being washed cleaned by the waters of life? or do i encourage the growth of dead rotting things in my life and body because i refuse to let go? 
how well do i bathe my body by drinking in the life giving, cleansing waters of pure juices and fluids that flush away the inner toxic debris? 
can i allow the waters of my tears to fall, cleansing my being of old unexpressed emotions and unresolved experiences that would harden me, closing me off to the life giving light of the sun and wandering winds of life?

are you receiving and flowing with the currents, the waters and energies of your life? or is there something or someone you are resisting, arguing and fighting against?

text:
trigger warning 
trauma venting part 2
-------------------
the pictures of text following contain graphic discriptions of s*xual ass*ult, substance ab*se, toxic and ab*us*ve relationship trauma, family ab*se trauma, brief mention of inc*st and csa, mentions of mental illness, chronic illness, neurodiversity as a sensitivity, lgbtqia relationship trauma, mentions purposeful misg*ndering, gaslighting, medical supplies,¬† h*melessness, disab*lity, bullying, public hum*liat*on.
-let me know if i need to add anything.
-------------------
so i added happy pictures of myself (no edit no filter) for an opening safe guard and also to represent my ability to myself that i am capable of healing and happiness even through all the nightmares i've lived. --
--
i have also added pictures of the physical representation of my innerworld's safe room. this is where i go when i need rest, recovery, and stress relief. i am happy to have a room in real life in which can physically represent my happy place. i thought i would share it and post it with this because its relevent to my healing and comfort when having to face my traumas.
--
stuffies featured in my happy place:
princess sugar puss the unicorn
marmaloo from cucumberland the unicorn
snackiemunchoos the unicorn
pickles the unicorn
penniigwen the penguin
boom boom the bass pig 
gbleep gbloop the giraffe (silent "g's")
toodles the puppy
puddles the puppy
bleubeary the bear
nini naners the monkey
giigii georgiio the giraffe
scribbles the kitten
leon the lion
koali jr. the koala
hipperhops the bunny
spooked'em the ghosty
--
my little baby ino chi doggo is of course, in my happy place as well. --
--
featuring unfinished artworks by me:
@foreveralwayslovinglettuce
--
thank you to those of you who took the time to read it all. --
--

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby," said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:

total lie she was convicted in criminal court. she said she only plead guilty for her family in order to end court and not drag her children through it. 
we motioned immediately, 4/28/15 we went to court for an emergency domestic violence restraining order to protect our family and for temporary measures to help her daughter through this. 
101 days later and four weeks after she plead guilty she tried to serve my husband with a restraining order and she goes to court saying she never touched either one of us and is afraid suddenly. 
i am sorry to say this but this woman is full of it and shame on the courts for allowing this to happen to us.  it is because of this experience that i developed chronic complex post traumatic stress disorder.  the further i got into this state the further my husband did. i was put on the stand twice and made to listen to myself

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
qanon fans are applying this same participatory behavior that we have celebrated in fiction fandom to real-world political drama. and why not? the boundaries between politics and entertainment have been collapsing for years. the entire trump presidency operates like reality tv, completely divorced from any real stakes or substance.

that‚Äôs what makes this all so terrifying. do these people really believe that tom hanks and hillary clinton are personally running a massive pedophilia ring? really??? but consider this: trump announced at a rally this week that the farmers being harmed by his stupid trade war had told him ‚Äúwe can take it.‚Äù no actual farmers said that to him. we all know that. but it‚Äôs a little thing, just part of the story we are all interacting with.

the pulsating heart of the qanon theory is not a lunatic fringe denying the real consequences of a failing presidency. the heart of it is a devoted fan base constructing elaborate theories to make the story more fun and engaging. and if you start from the premise that nothing government does matters, then it‚Äôs easy to come along for the ride. there‚Äôs no real difference between hillary clinton and the smoke monster. they‚Äôre both just characters on the television.

that‚Äôs what alarms me most about the growth of qanon. it‚Äôs not that these people are unhinged and possibly armed. it‚Äôs that we‚Äôve lost the capacity to treat civics, governance, and public affairs as though they have actual stakes with actual consequences. the premise of the trump presidency is that nothing matters, so you should root for your side and heckle the opposing team. he encourages his supporters to treat democrats and journalists like a rival fan base.

david karpf

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - i‚Äôve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now i‚Äôm about to go back, knowing what i know, and we‚Äôre about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trump‚Äôs election, trumpeted the return of their ‚Äúpopulist hero‚Äù on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publication‚Äôs announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if there‚Äôs any confusion out there, let me clear it up: i‚Äôm leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents ‚Äì on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

cnn

women are taught to hold keys out between their fingers when walking to the car. women are taught to not to go out at night alone, walk in groups, "dont dress slutty" or if you wear clothes that are too revealing you were "asking for it". women know to meet their dates in public places "just in case", not to put their drink down out of sight, check their backseat before getting in the car, carry a weapon, do not go jogging at night , watch your drink being poured,  don't wear both earbuds when running, and the list goes on. when the men were asked in this research study there was silence and "i don't think about it". ‚ñ™
instead of teaching women all the ways to avoid being raped how about we teach men not to rape! #endrapeculture .

text: reflections on this sb sunday as a pats & brady fan (cue eye roll from my ny friends, i know, but hear me out): yes, brady has shown support for trump as a friend and past colleague- they have a lot of history as successful celebrities & businessmen. but when it‚Äôs come down to the locker room & the field, brady wasn‚Äôt and still isn‚Äôt there to talk about why our president is/isn‚Äôt a great leader. they‚Äôre different people with different agendas, and they‚Äôre still allowed to be friends. what‚Äôs amazing about sports is that you have an entire team that is your closest family next to your actual family, and every single member of that family is entitled to their own beliefs based on their own personal life experiences. you & i have democrat friends who have republican parents or grandparents or cousins, and i can‚Äôt imagine us taking time out of our days to tweet about why they‚Äôre terrible people for staying loyal to their party. politics, among so many other polarized topics, hasn‚Äôt divided a locker room nearly to the extent of our country‚Äôs painful, long standing division. i think this is a perfect metaphor of how our govt and this entire country should strive to behave. democrat fans shaming brady and all of the hard work he put into his career just bc he has a maga hat in his locker is the same level of tunnel visioned bias as any republican that goes out of their way to say that actors who wear the #metoo pins are controversial and don‚Äôt have a credible career. i will always support celebrities who use their powerful platforms in meaningful ways. many of them do this on a daily basis, and many of them don‚Äôt. it‚Äôs not our right to misjudge their words or their silence. don‚Äôt hate the player or the team, and definitely don‚Äôt ruin the game, just because we were given an opportunity to peek into these peoples‚Äô lives (who are humans just like us) and hack it to pieces. i would wish that for no one, especially as we‚Äôre all trying to live our lives as peacefully as possible. sportsmanship isn‚Äôt just limited to the field. let‚Äôs at least try to preserve that! #foodforthought #letsjustplaysomefootball #happysuperbowl üèà

almost five years ago my husband and i hit the epirb on our boat and initiated an at-sea rescue for our youngest daughter, lyra. getting her medical attention was the right decision. we had no idea, however, what a fire-storm it would end up creating on land about the parenting choices of sailors.
.
the hardest part of this whole ordeal was not the massive media attention our story created, but the traumatic rescue itself and the loss of our home and our decade long dream to circumnavigate the world together. we spent the first few weeks of our return to land taking care of lyra, who continued to deal with several rounds of her illness, and trying to make sense of the abbreviation of our dream. it took us many years to overcome the loss and the story still reverberates throughout our lives.
.
almost two years ago i began to write a book about our experience. the book tells the unlikely story of how my husband and i met (a story i've never told publicly) and how we bought a sailboat, raised our kids aboard, and ended up in that dramatic rescue at sea.
.
i'm sharing this today because in the next month or two my book will go out on submission and i‚Äôll need a team of people who can help me get the word out about it. i‚Äôll be looking to do speakings & readings at book stores, libraries, sailing clubs, events, etc. and for ideas on podcasts and websites where i can talk about the themes in my story including: adventure, sailing, free-range parenting, mental health,¬†#metoo¬†and speaking out against sexual abuse.
.
part of publishing a book is publicity and marketing and for that i‚Äôll need your help. the group is an inclusive place where we can talk about the process of writing and publishing. it‚Äôs a safe place too, for us to share our stories and support each other, and ultimately, to help the¬†#rebelheartbook¬†make its way into the world.
.
i‚Äôll need a crew of people to help me through this process. will you join me there? we can connect our rebel hearts together:
.
group:¬†facebook.com/groups/charlottekaufmangroup
.
updates by email:¬†bit.ly/charlotteemaillist

text_retweet:
reposted from @charlievargasesq -  this is the time that we must decide to become human beings that are actually living and vibrating higher in this world as opposed to just existing in the midst of it. there will be mistakes along the way but i applaud my brother @kingkhepri from the @thelivesofmen for addressing this issue in the best way we know now and with good intentions leading the way.

#repost
#patriarchy is a system of oppression based on the notion that #men are superior to #women; particularly in education, social and economic status. as #feminist movements developed and sought to dismantle patriarchal structures, extreme forms of feminism emerged and became proxy‚Äôs for anti-maleness. in some cases, these movements became less about gaining equality for women and more about usurping power from men.

there has been a lot of public debate about how toxic men have been (#metoo and #timesup) and rightfully so, but we are missing a great opportunity to educate men and women about the effects of patriarchy, how we both uphold and support the system, and how it harms us - equally.

so here is what i think we should do to graduate this much needed conversation:
1. men - we have to get real honest with ourselves about how we keep messing up. take ownership and be willing to address really hard things about the way you‚Äôve shown up in the world. i‚Äôm talking to myself as i‚Äôm talking to you.

2. women - understand that #feminism, in it‚Äôs truest form is not the emasculation of men, it is the understanding that healing will not occur in isolation and by condemnation. it‚Äôll only occur by having serious dialogue - assuming number 1 above occurs.

3. women and men have to do a better job of listening and holding space for one another. this is difficult shit to unpack. until that happens, the result will be a bigger wedge between us and more finger pointing.

humbly,

jason 
#thelivesofmen

text:
in honor of #blackhistorymonth, we are highlighting black women leaders in our community, politics, the arts, and education throughout the month of february.
‚ú®
florynce "flo" kennedy was an attorney and civil rights activist. kennedy was among the first black women to graduate from columbia law school in the first half of the 20th century, and became a leader in the women's rights movement. she was the founder of the feminist party, which went on to sponsor the historic nomination of shirley chisolm for president of the united states in 1972.
‚ú®
kennedy's approach to activism centered on intersectionality; she often spoke and wrote about the pathological oppression of women, poor people, black people and people of color, and incarcerated individuals.

text:
your subconscious mind is listening to everything you put in front of it.  if you program yourself for negativity, you will stay there, this i promise you.

i saw this radio station option on my google play. "i'm not ok" radio. üò≥ wtf??! half of me is happy that suicide is being talked about openly however i have a deep abiding concern that people are riding the deep dark train in a trend. 
there is a difference between having a life event that is catastrophic and causes dark feelings and distress and clinical chemical depression.  don't buy into he hype.  do your best to get support, get out of the house, play a song that makes you happy, take a shower, do your makeup... change the routine of the emotions. see what you can do before you decided you need meds or are depressed.

as always, come see me if you need support. ~ carla 
www.karmaconnectionlv.com/book-online/

lets keep it 100!
.

you can watch the superbowl and still understand why people are taking a knee... you cannot watch the superbowl and still love the sport...
.
.
don't join in on something because it's trending... know why people are taking a knee... know why people are choosing to not watch the superbowl... .
.
i hope this video gives some insight into why some of us choose to take a knee... click on the link in bio for the full video!

it's a 3 minute video and i would love for you all to get the entire scope of what i'm saying... this is a divisive  issue... but it is a real issue that people are literally losing their life over... it's not about being disrespectful to the flag... it's about racial inequality and police brutality... that has always been the narrative despite those who seek to highjack it... if you disagree i still love you... but ask yourself why you disagree... and really be honest about it... let me know if you are more vocal about flag kneeling than police killings... but most importantly let me know if you have anything to add to the conversation... at the end of the day it's about equality and unity...

text:
metoo movement was not 1-year phenomenon in state capitols
#  file - in this feb. 7, 2018, file photo, sen. renee unterman, r-buford, ga., presents sb 352, in atlanta. barely a month into the 2019 legislative sessions, new policies against sexual misconduct already have been enacted or proposed in about one-fifth of the states as the #metoo movement enters its second year in state capitols amid continuing complaints of sexual wrongdoing. unterman, who was removed from a committee leadership post, publicly declared that "in the last couple of weeks, i have had sexual harassment against me." she has not provided any specific details about her allegations. (bob andres/atlanta journal-constitution via ap, file) (bob andres) jefferson city, mo. (ap) -- in the first week of 2019, an investigation by oregon's labor agency deemed the state capitol to be a hostile workplace because of an unchecked pattern of sexual harassment among lawmakers. a few days later, two washington state lawmakers accused of sexual misconduct resigned. then came new allegations of sexual wrongdoing in georgia, pennsylvania and massachusetts, where a veteran male lawmaker was accused of groping a newly elected female colleague during a pre-session reception. "we've heard for a long‚Ä¶

text:
this week @jimfalklexusbeverlyhills, i was sexually harassed by a salesman, while shopping for a used car.

i tried to brush off his advances & give him the benefit of the doubt at first.

he proceeded to manipulate me, and make false promises in regards to the car deal.

when i said no to his advancements and about buying the car, he got very nasty, verbally abused & threatened me.  i still can‚Äôt talk about all of the inappropriate said and done.

the next day i told management what happened.  they apologized to me but said they‚Äôve never heard of that happening before , so aren‚Äôt doing anything.  i have not even been reimbursed for the cars inspection or uber‚Äôs to the dealer.

i am so shooken up by this. i still can‚Äôt fully talk about it because i‚Äôm ashamed and scared to do so.
...
scared of people not believing me, afraid of making it a big deal, afraid of hurting the guys career, wanting to be nice and quiet about it, afraid of what people will say about me, and embarrassed that i didn‚Äôt figure it out and put a stop to it sooner .

how is this still possible? .
...
i took action against the creeper who broke into my apt pantsless before metoo started. (granted it took me almost 2 years to have the courage)

i eventually stood up to my landlord for enabling the creeper.

i‚Äôve seen countless women say me too .

i still feel like i should be a lady and shouldn‚Äôt post this.

i don‚Äôt want to post this. 
i don‚Äôt want to make it a thing.

i can‚Äôt be an enabler by keeping quiet though.

so here goes.

#metoo #metooagain #lexus #carshopping #metooed #stopenabling #holdenablersaccountable @alyraisman #beverlyhills #losangeles #standup #courage @lexususa #carsforsale

text:
so wonderful to be celebrating two years sober with this view! 
two years ago this week i checked myself into treatment right down the street, i could not stop the cycle of binge drinking and overeating, hated myself and felt i was nothing but a failure. for years i wanted to rent my own beach bungalow in malibu but my debt, drinking and single status held me back from. i thought only losers vacation alone and that i would wait for a boyfriend. everything i believed was wrong today i am living my dream life... sober, transformation body and debt free and it's actually really really special to be alone and know that i don't have to wait for a boyfriend, my life is simply amazing because i created it through my own hard work, intelligence and commitment to myself !! anything is possible, anything can be üíì

#onedayatatime #recoveroutloud #sober #weightlossjourney #empoweringwomen #nohangover #noalcohol #metoo #malibu #californiadreaming

text:
tw: mentions of abuse, trauma, suicide "honestly?

shoutout to the people who have been through abuse and are trying to be better than that.

to everyone who‚Äôs going against all of their instincts telling them to shut down, and trying to communicate well anyway.

to everyone using the hashtag #metoo. to everyone who can‚Äôt use the hashtag #metoo.

to everyone who doesn‚Äôt remember what happened, but they‚Äôre trying to be careful.

to everyone who used to externalize their pain, and now are internalizing it, or vice versa, but are trying to find a balance.

to everyone who isn‚Äôt sure if they‚Äôll ever be mentally healthy enough to have ‚Äúgood‚Äù relationships, but they‚Äôre trying their hardest anyway.

to everyone who apologizes really strongly when they mess up.

to everyone whose parents have given up on them, to everyone wounded by the bystander effect, to everyone who was the last one to know about their own trauma.

to everyone with physical and mental illnesses.

to everyone who‚Äôs used to being dismissed by people who should care about them, and they‚Äôre trying to take care of themselves anyway.

to everyone whose memory isn‚Äôt enough.

to everyone who‚Äôs trying to live past when they thought they would kill themselves.

to everyone who isn‚Äôt sure what happened was ‚Äúbad enough.‚Äù to everyone who needs more validation about trauma stuff but even their most supportive people are invalidating or triggering.

to everyone with a personality disorder who worries that their mental illness invalidates their abuse.

to everyone who can‚Äôt tell how much information they‚Äôre saying is oversharing because they were so used to being invalidated and then not talking.

to everyone whose therapists haven‚Äôt called it abuse, but know it was abusive.

to everyone discovering their anger after being so quiet for so long.

to everyone whose anger feels explosive.

to everyone who has really mixed feelings about the people who abused them and/or their abuse.

to everyone who has a mix of repressed memories and flashbacks.

to everyone who wants and needs to talk about their trauma, but they‚Äôre not sure who they could trust and who would be validating.

text:
"self portrait". the past (left) has a lot of dark things in it. but i'm on my way to the bright, blank page where i can mould my future the way i want it to be (hopefully). i'm surrounded by a warm, good aura but shadowed by the past darkness. i'm finding the good things in life finally. even after suffering through abuse and neglect for so many years. 
the black blobs are the many bad things that happened to me. my mother's mental and financial abuse and neglect. my ex's physical, mental and sexual abuse. school bullying. my dad's anger. my depression. so many things. 
#art #watercolor #ink #mentalhealth #selfportrait #abuse #neglect #metoo

text:
i don't drink poison hoping someone else will die. -ashley judd

when asked by teri gross, on her show fresh air, whether she forgave harvey weinstein for his sexual assault that's how ashley judd responded. she said above all she forgave him for herself. not to do so would be to linger in that place of trauma and relive it forever. this struck a chord with me. i have never been sexually assaulted, but i was bullied in grade school and physically and emotionally abused by my father. for years i struggled with anger and insecurity stemming from those experiences. i even began perpetrating the same emotional pain on others, all while punishing myself. i felt locked in a cycle of negative expectation and the fulfillment of that expectation. the change came, when like ashley, i forgave my abusers. did i meet with them face-to-face? no, i didn't. that isn't required, and sometimes shouldn't be done, depending upon the situation. i forgave them in my own heart and stopped drinking the poison of hate i had been force feeding myself for decades. i reengineered my mind to accept the positive side of myself, and therefore of all humanity. we're far from perfect, but that's ok. if you focus on the negative you can be sure that's what you are consuming, you are trapping yourself in a condition that will only reflect what you have come to expect - what you manifest. put that cup down, you owe it to yourself.

#healing #enlightenedlife #spirituality #betterlife #vegan #totalhealth #humanity #peace #metoo #emotionalhealing #survivor #warriorspirit

text: the anger i felt toward certain newspapers and bbc radio4's click bait coverage of margaret, duchess of argyll has turned into anxiety. i'm anxious people will think my book is a misogynistic portrayal of a woman who was so badly treated in 1963 and thereafter. i can assure you, it is not, nor did i partake in interviews with the sun, daily mirror, etc, despite them printing quotes from my book's press release. i explore a new side to margaret's life, and i hope you will see her as a human-being rather than an object of scandal. #margaretduchessofargyll #margofarg #books #timesup #metoo #feminism #womeninhistory #aristocracy #history #womenshistory #argyll

text: i started my career as an actress on this stage @cameritheatre of tlv, at the age of 17. today i stood there with no part in a play, no costumes or imaginary world. i spoke as me, in my own words, about the real world. exchanging ideas is the key to happiness. it was an honor to be part of a special evening by @barilanuniversity about the future of #metoo in poetry, law and culture. when truth and dialogue happen, magic follows. it was one of those evenings, where i was proud to be part of the human race, heading in the right direction.

text:
last sunday, our preacher shared a lesson based on the story of david and bathsheba.  i‚Äôm going to start calling this the story of ‚Äúdavid, uriah, and nathan‚Äù now because i never realized how small a part bathsheba‚Äôs (more often referred to as ‚Äúthe wife of uriah‚Äù in the text) is in a story that turned her life upside down so completely. the lamb in nathan‚Äôs narrative gets more air time.
.
bathsheba, in the text is noted mostly as something stolen, and how consequences represent for david.  i haven‚Äôt watched any of the dramatizations of this story, but from a brief overview from imdb of the 1951 movie ‚Äúdavid and bathsheba‚Äù their relationship is described as ‚Äúan affair‚Äù. a seduction.  not a brutal example of power and abuse. (of course it was made in the 50‚Äôs..) .
what struck me the most is that we still do this to women who are victims. we pontificate about what they were wearing, why didn‚Äôt they watch their drink, why didn‚Äôt they put up more of a fight?  it‚Äôs like asking why didn‚Äôt bathsheba, home alone, resist the guards the king sent to retrieve her? did she even know why she received a royal summons?
.
i realized i have a lot of questions about this story. i wrote an open letter to bathsheba, that i‚Äôm sharing on my blog, if you‚Äôre interested in reading more. (link in bio)
.

.

text:
he doesn‚Äôt share his story like i do mine but if he did you‚Äôd realize how incredible it is that he‚Äôs such an amazing human.
‚òÄÔ∏è
there are so many walking miracles yet most people are uncomfortable sharing the storms that made them who they are. storms are nothing to be ashamed of, they‚Äôre what makes trees take deeper roots and the deeper your roots the better you can withstand the storms.
‚òÄÔ∏è
a lot of what i‚Äôve endured has been beyond my control but not all of it. no, many weathered storms were a natural consequence of my actions ... and i realize that, i‚Äôve had an easier time healing from those wounds. it‚Äôs the situations i had no control over that cut deep and left the most vibrant scars.
‚òÄÔ∏è
have you walked through pain and suffering that you were born into? forced into? it‚Äôs the hardest to heal, am i right?
‚òÄÔ∏è
you know what i‚Äôve realized though? we can absolutely acknowledge that trauma, own it, share it, cry about it, grieve over it, pick it apart and live.
‚òÄÔ∏è
not survive and exist but fully live despite and in spite of it.
‚òÄÔ∏è
we can be full of pure joy and spend time feeling the pain wash back over our souls. we can have it all figured out and question it a moment later.
‚òÄÔ∏è
what we can‚Äôt do is allow those that marched us through hell to hold the key to our peace, our happiness, our healing. they may have ghost wrote several chapters but your book isn‚Äôt over yet and you have the power to take the pen back and write the next one!

text:
today in black history we honor the silence 
we the silent screams of our foremothers
the screams swallowed 
while we were raped 
the screams tucked into the darkest places 
of our souls 
so as not to wake the children 
and see more horror in their eyes 
so as not to wake the men 
and see the pain of not being able to protect us 
the emasculation of being powerless 
when master rapes your wife 
we the sobs hushed 
we the refrains muffled 
we the words that didn‚Äôt part from our teeth 
because 
we did best to know our place 
we did best not to be uppity 
or think that we may deserve dignity 
we that learned a down cast eye 
kept us alive 
we the tears flowing like waterfalls 
perpetually inside 
while our sons swung 
high 
and died 
our feet bleed beneath our skin 
our backs shredded within 
our lips closed and tight 
our tongue tattooed with perpetual bite 
we learned to suffer in silence to save ourselves
to save our men and children 
we learned too well 
we the tired 
we the weary
we the screams
we the sirens
we are silent no more 
you will hear us 
our feet marching 
with the screams of our ancestors at our backs 
like wind in our sails 
vengeance that has laid waiting for too long 
we will open our mouths 
and you will never hear the same again 
our screams will echo in your souls forever 
our #metoo began before hollywood 
before trump grabbed pussies 
stand with your alabaster tears 
for as long as you can 
but move when you hear my army 
move when you hear my battle cry 
move when you feel the presence of my lineage

text:
ashley- what do you actually do ?
fair question ‚ú®
in 2008 i realized that the corporate world wasn‚Äôt for me after the bank i worked for went bankrupt. i experimented remote work a bit with my boss and i loved it... (thanks @rhys_spencer ) 
i started learning values work - what was truly driving me, how i wanted to spend my time and what helped me make decisions. i realized i wanted to - and could- create my dream life and go live it.
i started working in tourism and lived for 4years out of my backpack, and started life/health coaching and teaching.
in 2011 i developed some intense anxiety and depression and lived through my very own and very scary #metoo experience.
in 2013 i realized running was saving my life and combined my passion for fun physical activity with my coaching experience and i pitched @sole_girls for the first time.
i have since been rooted in #vancouver growing powerful programs, workshops and camps for tweens and their supporters to help them navigate communication, values, emotions, friendships and mental health.
in 2016 #solegirls began licensing the programs across canada and in australia üá¶üá∫ .
2019 is the year i launch something very special that i‚Äôve been working on called #soleschool and my very first book called ‚Äúa girls guide to finding her happy pace‚Äù .
üéØüëâüèºthe pre launch is happening at the end of this week and i am so freaking excited i could cry. üò≠ü§Ø
‚òÄÔ∏è so why am i on a beach? .
because i gosh darn want to be and i‚Äôve been building my life in a way that supports this.  also-fun fact- i‚Äôm getting more done here than i do in the city.  i have had exponential amounts of clarity since being here. 
also- i want girls to grow up knowing that dreams do come true and the universe will support them.  also a lot of hard work, hustle, planning, values work, listening, letting go, and budgeting help a whole lot too. 
so what?
game on friends. let‚Äôs create dream lives. also- please support my book üìñ üòõ

one in five women in college will experience sexual assault. unfortunately, @caelynnmillerkeyes was one of them. on tonight‚Äôs episode of the bachelor, caelynn opened up about her experience being sexually assaulted when she was a sophomore in college. we want to thank her for being so open about what happened to her, and for using the platform she has gained through the bachelor to spread awareness about an issue that is all too common. thank you, caelynn, for everything you have done for survivors by speaking out about your experience. we support you and all survivors.‚Å£
‚Ä¢‚Å£
survivors like caelynn remind us that there is a light after all that darkness. ‚Äúit weakens you. it really does. it was the darkest time in my life,‚Äù she said, speaking about her experience. but she continued, going on about how she has been able to continue with her recovery. ‚Äúmy focus is on survivors,‚Äù she explained. ‚Äúi want to help other people who are hiding out and feel like their voices are restricted. i really am so much stronger now, in so many ways.‚Äù ‚Å£
‚Ä¢‚Å£
if you or someone you know has experienced sexual assault and/or was affected by tonight‚Äôs episode of the bachelor, please take a second to check out the resources available 24/7 at @rainn , as well as the national and international resources available in the link in our bio under ‚Äúresources.‚Äù we are here for you.‚Å£
‚Ä¢‚Å£

text: cariann here, founder at @midnight.woman and @l.odet. i‚Äôve loved watching the bachelor the last couple seasons. it‚Äôs a fascinating show! last week contestant caelynn miller-keyes shared her #metoo story with colton, this season‚Äôs bachelor. i‚Äôm really impressed with the way the show let her tell her story without exploiting it for views. it was on her terms. i just want to commend @caelynnmillerkeyes for her bravery and thank her for sharing this on national television. we have a long way to go with talking about sexual assault, but this is an important step. also seeing a man not make this about himself was commendable and inspiring. thanks @bachelorabc for handling this well. we need more meaningful topics covered in reality television. we stand with you, caelynn ‚ú®

text:
my trans brother was severely sexually harassed at work yesterday. an older male coworker was talking with him and referred to him as a "chick". my brother corrected him, explaining that he is a man with a hormone disorder. and instead of respecting my brother, believing him, and moving on, the fucking douchebag would not let it go. he questioned my brother, asking him, "why do you have boobs? why don't you have an adams apple?" etc, to which my brother explained these are all due to his aforementioned hormone disorder. finally, the guys asks, "do you have a dick?" to which my brother says yes. and then this sick freak asks my brother "if he can touch it." my brother reported the asshole to their supervisor, and now we are praying the guy gets fired. this isn't the first time he has sexually harassed a fellow employee, and a second warning is far too light for this level of verbal assault. sick of men who think they have a right to make others, whether male or female, feel threatened and insignificant. shit like this is fucking seriously not okay. when men say things like this, they are fully aware of how they are making the recipient feel; there are no "mistakes" is a situation like this. we should all expect respect from our comrades and peers, not belittlement and degrading sexual language.
so here's a color test of native dyes as a rainbow of love for all of us who are part of the lgbt+ community. we deserve respect. we deserve kindness. we deserve empathy. and men like that need their fucking asses kicked.

i've watched the qspiracy since day one.

steve bannon left the wh august 2017 and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? 'j-c' church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt, with the goonsquad known as gop, has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

with that being said always follow you #instinct even if everyone is against you. you might just save yourself in the end from harm. it doesn't matter who believes you and who doesn't. you know the truth, god knows the truth that's what matters. do what you must do to continue moving forward. some days are harder than others, sometimes you still feel the lingering effects of what happened. you have to keep that head up and keep moving forward, and most importantly you have to make sure your mental and physical health are good.
#mentalhealthawareness
#trauma
#metoo

text:
- what we worked on was ... data harvesting programs where we would pull data from users of apps and all of their friend networks and run that data through algorithms that could profile their personality traits and other psychological attributes, wylie told cnn‚Äôs don lemon monday evening.

wylie said the ultimate goal was to obtain information in order to exploit mental vulnerabilities that our algorithms showed that [facebook users] had.

in addition to wylie and cambridge analytica, accounts of cambridge analytica‚Äôs parent company, strategic communication laboratories, and those of a university of cambridge psychologist aleksandr kogan were also suspended.

the accounts were suspended because facebook received reports that data that had been shared with cambridge and wylie from kogan‚Äôs app may not have been completely deleted. kogan‚Äôs app was removed in 2015 and facebook said they had been previously provided certifications that the data had been deleted. - several days ago, we received reports that, contrary to the certifications we were given, not all data was deleted, facebook said friday. - we are moving aggressively to determine the accuracy of these claims. if true, this is another unacceptable violation of trust and the commitments they made. we are suspending scl/cambridge analytica, wylie and kogan from facebook, pending further information.

special counsel robert mueller asked cambridge analytica last fall to surrender emails from any of its employees who worked for the trump campaign, the wall street journal reported in december. the firm complied to the request.

diana stancy correll
washington examiner

text:
it‚Äôs #childrensmentalhealthweek 
mental health problems affect about 1 in 10 children and young people. they include depression, anxiety and conduct disorder, and are often a direct response to what is happening in their lives.

alarmingly, however, 70% of children and young people who experience a mental health problem have not had appropriate interventions at a sufficiently early age.

the emotional wellbeing of children is just as important as their physical health. good mental health allows children and young people to develop the resilience to cope with whatever life throws at them and grow into well-rounded, healthy adults.

things that can help keep children and young people mentally well include:

being in good physical health, eating a balanced diet and getting regular exercise
having time and the freedom to play, indoors and outdoors
being part of a family that gets along well most of the time
going to a school that looks after the wellbeing of all its pupils
taking part in local activities for young people.
other factors are also important, including:

feeling loved, trusted, understood, valued and safe
being interested in life and having opportunities to enjoy themselves
being hopeful and optimistic
being able to learn and having opportunities to succeed
accepting who they are and recognising what they are good at
having a sense of belonging in their family, school and community
feeling they have some control over their own life
having the strength to cope when something is wrong (resilience) and the ability to solve problems.
most children grow up mentally healthy, but surveys suggest that more children and young people have problems with their mental health today than 30 years ago. that‚Äôs probably because of changes in the way we live now and how that affects the experience of growing up.

text:
hi i'm uriel welcome to my recovery account! probably daily updates on my mental state will be posted... almost like a diary but not rlly lol

so i've been inpatient in the hospital 7 times for mental health reasons and rehab once. while i'm doing better, im working hard to keep my positivity up. part of me hopes people will follow this account for support, because my dms are always open. i'll also be sure to put a trigger warning on any posts that might be a little dark, because sometimes i have those thoughts and they need to be expressed! today has been honestly a really tough day, just because some drugs were around me and i felt big big uncomfortable :( here's to my attempt at staying sober!

#depression #bpd #mentalhealth #sobriety #selfharm #recovery #survivor #metoo #support #anxiety #motivation

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election. - one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
cruel, dark sweet. 
oh, i'd never let you take all of me. 
indeterminable hours your clever hands spent just missing their mark.
it was a strange relief to share your insatiable need for dominance. 
inclement barbs, practical gifts, knots and bruises,
picking up my frantic calls when my anxiety tried to drown me in its shadow.
each of us bewildered as we incessantly clashed with an opponent that would not yield.
the cost of loving people like us is steep.
but, you taught me that perhaps my clenched fists were simply a symptom of needless shame and a faintly beating heart.

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - i‚Äôve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now i‚Äôm about to go back, knowing what i know, and we‚Äôre about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trump‚Äôs election, trumpeted the return of their ‚Äúpopulist hero‚Äù on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publication‚Äôs announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if there‚Äôs any confusion out there, let me clear it up: i‚Äôm leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents ‚Äì on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby," said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn
