text:
photo: noct and prompto sit on a military bunkbed, facing away from each other. they look at the ground, filled with remorse and fear respectively. noct says ‚Äúonce this is all over, i say we break down the borders - come together as one nation.‚Äù
ÂÜôÁúüÔºö„Éé„ÇØ„Éà„Å®„Éó„É≠„É≥„Éó„Éà„ÅåËªç‰∫ãÁî®ÔºíÊÆµ„Éô„ÉÉ„Éâ„Å´ËÉå‰∏≠„ÅÇ„Çè„Åõ„Å¶Â∫ß„Å£„Å¶„ÅÑ„Çã„ÄÇ„Éé„ÇØ„Éà„ÅØÂæåÊÇî„Åß„ÄÅ„Éó„É≠„É≥„Éó„Éà„ÅØÊÅê„Çå„Åß2‰∫∫„Å®„ÇÇÈ†≠„Çí„Å∂„Çä‰∏ã„Åí„Å¶„ÅÑ„Çã„ÄÇ„Éé„ÇØ„Éà„ÅØ„Äå„Åì„Çå„ÅåÁµÇ„Çè„Å£„ÅüÊúÄÂæå„ÄÅÂ¢ÉÁïå„ÇíÂèñ„ÇäÂ£ä„Åù„ÅÜ„ÄÇÔºë„Å§„ÅÆÂõΩ„Å®„Åó„Å¶ÈõÜ„Åæ„Çã„Äç

final fantasy xv (or final fantasy bro trip as it is jokingly known as) is not the most radical game, but the director said it was his take on toxic masculinity. the depiction of certain characters (*cough* shiva) and body types (buff men, skinny women) aside, male intimacy was the highlight. it is still restrictive, but it‚Äôs a step, and all steps count. men cry. men have weak moments. men care for each other. men wish to belong to each other. i admittedly do enjoy the slash element of it, but two guys shouldn‚Äôt have to be gay to feel for each other, and girls like luna shouldn‚Äôt be the sole bearers of male emotions. this game does that.¬†
like with 10 and 13, i enjoy the majority/minority dynamic that is appearing in stories. prompto was almost coming out. japan really does take baby steps, but stories like this can help people understand the need for diversity.¬†
plus, anything about breaking down borders is good ^_^ however if people‚Äôs are going to be amalgamated, you must prevent erasure of identities, as the japanese government does with zainichi koreans.

text:
25 days from launch!!
in honor of the count down, i'm going to be posting every day with 27 life lessons that i've learned in my 27 years! „Ää3. you are not your past traumas.„Äã ‚ô° //tw\\ here's the heavy. we all knew this one was coming right? i won't go into specifics, because this is neither the time nor the place. there isn't a "bright" side to it, or a way to see sunshines and rainbows. however, i was around 3 years old when it happened to me. it wasn't until september-ish of 2018 that i sat down with my mom and we finally talked about it. it wasn't a conversation that either one of us were prepared for. it was a conversation that she never expected to have with me. i just needed to know that the dreams i had were real, and that i wasn't crazy. it's a very strange feeling having to come to terms and understand something this traumatic that happened to you 26 years ago. but to me, it is like it happened yesterday because i now have the memory gaps filled in. looking back, there is no doubt, that past trauma has affected how i approach relationships in my life. i'm currently dealing with something that my family has taken years to overcome. it makes sense, that some days it's very hard for me to focus on daily tasks when i'm trying to process what happened. the first thing i said to my mom, was "they say 1 in 5 women are sexually assaulted. so if that means i had to be the one for you and my 3 nieces to be safe, then i'll take on that burden. i feel just bad for all of you and my brothers." nothing happened to them, but they had to go through it with me, and live with it daily, while watching me grow up hoping that it wouldn't leave lasting effects. i was hurt to hear that for them, and most days i still am. it wasn't my fault as to why that happened, and if it happened to you then it wasn't your fault either. i encourage you to talk it out with someone you trust. it's okay not to be be okay. it's okay to feel hurt and sickened and scared. but it is never okay to use that as an excuse to hurt someone else. you are not your past traumas and it is 100% okay to learn and heal. ‚ù§

text:
yes. i don't think people understand it unless they too have been in this situation. the mind is a wondrous thing but sometimes it feels like it can be such a burden to even have a mind when you're struggling with thoughts and flashbacks racing through it. you want to turn it off, but it just feels impossible. this alone is stressful enough, but when someone recognizes that your mind is elsewhere and asks you what's wrong, it can be so difficult to describe it. it's the same with knowing you should probably talk to someone about what you're going through, but you just feel as though there's no way anyone will quite understand what you're experiencing, especially if you don't quite understand it yourself.
‚Ä¢
please just know if you feel this way, you are not alone. it seems as though people don't understand, but trust me, they do. we do. maybe not everyone understands what you're going through, but there are plenty of people who do. each persons experience is different, but we can relate to the pain and stress of feeling as though others do not understand.
‚Ä¢
if you need to talk to someone, i'm just a dm away. i'm not an expert by any means, but i have been through trauma and dealt with the symptoms of ptsd and i know a lot of good sources to direct you towards, including anonymous helplines and online chats with health professionals that are available 24 hrs a day to talk/message you with helpful tips on how to cope and heal from what you've been through.
‚Ä¢
for awhile, i didn't want to talk to someone about it, but it honestly just kept eating away at me. talking about it helped soothe the pain, even if it was just a little at a time. i know it can feel nerve wrecking to talk to someone about what you're going through, but it really can help.
üíô

text:
"if power mainly resides with men, what does this imply for accountability? if the world is unfair, who is responsible for making it right? this cannot be a burden just for women. we men must play an active role in ensuring a more just world. we men must not only be part of gender equality, not just a conversation, but the solution. we men must defy the structures of patriarchy and the outdated notions of manhood and use that questioning to build more justice societies."
_
powerful speech by @winstoncduke at the @heforshe impact summit, @unitednations

text:
long post alert, the background for those of you who don't know.
3 weeks ago today i was in the worst possible place i could be. i had planned the weekend accordingly and had said goodbye to friends and my beautiful family without them realising. i went out for coffee and cake with my incredible mr and children and then made my way to a bridge over the motorway to take my own life. i was stopped very quickly by a persistant but lovely man (i don't know who he is) he stayed with me and called the police. i ended up sectioned obviously and had no idea what to do. i had hurt everyone around me yet knew i couldn't cope with what was going on in my head and the days that were to come. i spent a long time in that hospital room on my knees praying completely broken. i actually got discharged in the early hours and made it to court the next day with the support of amazing friends and an ever supportive husband even after all i had done. i had to give evidence against a childhood abuser and be cross examined. it was the hardest thing i have ever done and i thought it would kill me. in actual fact it freed me! i have spent my life in a tangle of messed up thoughts, shame, guilt, disgust, self-hate, anger, every negative emotion you can think of and more. i have expressed that in eating disorders, a personality disorder and self harm. 
the trial actually mistrialed due to the jury unable to agree and i thought i was going straight back into the prison of my mind. the evening i found that out, a few hours later, i had a verse notification on phone that couldn't have answered my fears any clearer.
today i am so so happy to be here. to be spending the day with my children, husband and friends who i love so very much and who i now actually believe love me! i have had breakfast, i am 3 weeks self harm free, have no intentions of doing it again and have plans to tattoo over the scars. i am using my freedom to love. i have learnt i am loved and that i can put my trust in god. i am seeing the stars üòä
#survivor #speak #freedom #love #trustingod #holdon #heldup #metoo #timeforchange #recovery #suicide #thankyou #happy
name: Revivify Life

text:
i had an amazing day yesterday in london speaking with a wonderful group of ladies @tfc_thefemaleclub all about the female body and our relationship with it.
‚≠êÔ∏è
one of the ladies pointed out how she felt so much judgement of our body‚Äôs comes from other women rather than men. i have to admit, this has been my experience too, whether it‚Äôs been ‚Äòwell meaning‚Äô comments, subtle judgement or full on body shaming in women‚Äôs magazines. whether the articles are written by men or women, invariably they‚Äôre about a women‚Äôs body and those articles are bought and read by women.
‚≠êÔ∏è
i offered my perspective on this, rather than it being about her, actually what she was experiencing was the other woman‚Äôs projection of her own insecurity, of her own body shame, of the judgement of her own body.
‚≠êÔ∏è
this really highlights something essential to know, especially in today‚Äôs #metoo , patriarchy and toxic masculinity era. are we as women spreading our own pain and unhealed relationship with our body‚Äôs over every other woman in our lives? are we as women perpetuating the disempowerment of the feminine by keeping this cultural obsession with thinness alive, daily?
‚≠êÔ∏è
taking your power back means realising it‚Äôs yours already. nobody is going to give it to you. you just have to take it. one of the most powerful ways we as women can do this today is look through kinder eyes, at our own body and of other women‚Äôs body. to take responsibility for our own healing journey and not project on to other women, onto our daughters. to hold ourself within love and know the light that we each are.
‚≠êÔ∏è
in my book #yourbeutifulbody i ask you to make a beutiful promise, to never judge or criticise your body, or anyone else‚Äôs again. powerful. revolutionary. truly transformation, when we commit to thisüôèüèªüíû
.

the incident. i was petrified. i was trying to sleep after drinking a lot. i was passing out. couldn't move my limbs. and then he assaulted me.

text:
step 11 of our #16stepprogram - on how boys and men can step up and take action for #metoo.

check your personal behaviour

in trying to create a gender equal society, it is also important to self-reflect on issues like class, caste, gender, race, sexuality, identity, power, and economic status. people‚Äôs identities intersect in any given situation. recognise your own privilege and conditioned problematic behaviour like mansplaining, toxic masculinity, lack of consent, etc. this exercise will, more often than not, be painful for your ego but the idea is to become a person with whom women feel safe, heard, respected and valued as equals.
~in collaboration with @thepixelproject

text:
i'm thinking about journeys today.

specifically, about my own. how far i've come these last ten years, what it's cost and what i've gained.

sometimes i think we're so caught up in the future, in where we're going and how fast we can get there, that sometimes we forget to look back. to take stock. to check our progress and congratulate ourselves a little.

last week, i posted a (ginger) photo of me as a teenager. i talked about some of the things teenage me achieved and how much she had left to face. looking back at all the things that silly little redhead managed, i'm damn proud. and i'm not ashamed to admit it.

if i could go back and give myself some advice, i'd tell myself to take a break now and then. i'd tell myself that conquering the world doesn't have to mean wearing yourself to the bone. i'd tell myself that success is relative and that i'm doing enough.

what i've learned from the first ten years of adulthood is that i don't need to be rich, or to work at a big 4 consulting firm, or to own my own business, to be successful. those things i set out to achieve back in 2010... they neglected to mention happiness, fulfilment, the free time needed to be creative. to write.

if i could go back and talk to my old self, i'd tell myself never to let go of my biggest, longest-standing dream... to write.

#qotd: if you could go back and give some advice to your younger self, which self would you talk to, and what would you say?

#openbookshelf

text:
she decides is a global movement to ensure every girl and woman can decide what to do with her body, with her life, and with her future. this right affects her personal development, her participation in society, her livelihood and whether her family and community thrives.
and when she decides the world is better, stronger, safer. she decides whether, when, and with whom. to have sex, to fall in love, to marry, to have children. she has the right to information, to health care, to choose. she is free to feel pleasure. to use contraception. to decide.
we - and you, and he, and they - are coming together to say that for women and girls to truly be free, only she must decide what happens with her body.
this is a fundamental human right that must be upheld.
because when others decide for her, she faces violence, forced marriage oppression. she faces risks to her health, to her dignity, to her dreams,
to her life.
join the shedecides manifesto, and  thousands of people, companies, organizations and countries standing up to say we want a new normal: where every girl and woman, everywhere, can decide. without question.

she decides is a global movement to ensure every girl and woman can decide what to do with her body, with her life, and with her future. this right affects her personal development, her participation in society, her livelihood and whether her family and community thrives.
and when she decides the world is better, stronger, safer. she decides whether, when, and with whom. to have sex, to fall in love, to marry, to have children. she has the right to information, to health care, to choose. she is free to feel pleasure. to use contraception. to decide.
we - and you, and he, and they - are coming together to say that for women and girls to truly be free, only she must decide what happens with her body.
this is a fundamental human right that must be upheld.
because when others decide for her, she faces violence, forced marriage oppression. she faces risks to her health, to her dignity, to her dreams,
to her life.
join the shedecides manifesto, and  thousands of people, companies, organizations and countries standing up to say we want a new normal: where every girl and woman, everywhere, can decide. without question.

thank you to the family, friends and communities who respect and support my choice, muslim women‚Äôs choice to wear the hijab.

text:
sexual assault/abuse seems to be the real gina haunting the liberian society.
although, as more conversations surround the topic now more than ever, it is important we remember to use the opportunity to educate. not bully, not chastise, not castigate.
.
.
for so long in the liberian society, the topic has been sort of taboo - ‚Äújust forget about it‚Äù - our communities tell us. but now more than ever, we are not only remembering it, we are discussing it and speaking up against it.
while we understand the depths needed in the dialogue, and how triggering it can be for survivors, it is important we use the opportunity to educate others who are misinformed or appear ignorant to the discourse. .
.
to the people who are ignorant to it, please allow yourselves the opportunity to realize where you are wrong, and remove yourself from harmful thinking and practices that counteracts the progress survivors are making in furthering the discourse. .
.
welcome to the new week! allow yourself room to learn and to teach.
.
.
#koloquadialogues #liberia #metoo #monrovia #tabootopics

text:
how the trump administration‚Äôs title ix proposals threaten to undo #metoo
#
education secretary betsy devos holds a news conference at the education department on july 13, 2017, after a day of meetings weighing whether to keep or reject obama-era guidance for how schools must meet their obligations under title ix, a federal law that prohibits sex discrimination at federally funded institutions. (evelyn hockstein for the washington post) ruth lawlor is a phd candidate in history at the university of cambridge and a fox international fellow at yale. february 4 at 6:00 am the trump administration is trying to change title ix, the landmark federal legislation that prohibits discrimination in education on the basis of sex. proponents of the changes claim that the new rules better protect the due process rights of accused students, while also addressing real, and long-standing, racial disparities in rape allegations. in reality, however, the changes simply roll back protections for sexual assault victims, while doing nothing to actually address the issue of racial bias in rape cases. this is because the proposed changes center on a false dichotomy, one that frames civil rights for men of color and protections for rape victims as a zero-sum game. in doing so, the proposal relies on the persistent power of‚Ä¶

text:
personally speaking my mom's told me 'id rather have a dead daughter than a gay one' when i got her to watch #prayersforbobby with me as a 16 yr old (before ever coming out)...i first started hinting about 'what would you do mom/dad if i liked girls' since i was in middle school...always got the same 'i will not have an abomination in my home..... this is a god fearing home'...then i got older and these lesbian thoughts were not going away...i became an adult and decided to ask a college male friend to have sex with me to "change my thinking" *poor younger me who felt like she had to put herself through that* then i met a girl when i moved away to school and thought we'd end up together and decided to officially just tell my mom that i like girls...she cursed me out told me not to tell her people (family) and hung up on me. 
today i'm still lesbian af...i've become so desensitized to her and her bfs bigotry...idc
